1
00:00:00,385 --> 00:00:07,059
My job is just to put what we're doing in the context of the Buddha's teaching.

2
00:00:11,407 --> 00:00:21,027
In terms of his own particular passage, the Buddha, remember that one of his awakening moments, like when he first sort of

3
00:00:21,394 --> 00:00:36,939
begins to get this disaffection with life, with the ordinary way that he was living, was when after a party he saw everybody dishevelled, puking, all the usual stuff that you see after a party.

4
00:00:37,960 --> 00:00:47,113
And he saw these bodies and stuff hanging around, and it brought a certain disgust about the whole body to him.

5
00:00:47,715 --> 00:00:49,798
And the way that...

6
00:00:50,317 --> 00:00:52,502
The body draws you into indulgence.

7
00:00:53,122 --> 00:00:59,051
Now, that would have been his understanding when he practiced these mortification exercises that he went into.

8
00:00:59,072 --> 00:01:03,960
There would have been a presumption that the body is really the one to blame.

9
00:01:04,301 --> 00:01:08,968
So, if you didn't have hunger, you wouldn't have greed, full stop.

10
00:01:10,213 --> 00:01:20,487
So when you look at all our appetites, basic appetites, our sexual appetites, our eating appetites, all that sort of stuff, it's all grounded in the body.

11
00:01:21,087 --> 00:01:23,891
And it would seem that the signals come from the body.

12
00:01:25,373 --> 00:01:29,319
And therefore it's easy to make the mistake that, well, it's the body that's at fault.

13
00:01:29,799 --> 00:01:33,844
And somehow I've got to subdue the body, I've got to keep the body down.

14
00:01:34,646 --> 00:01:39,832
And in doing so I can control the body, and in doing so I can control the mind.

15
00:01:40,251 --> 00:01:43,737
And to a certain extent I think that's true.

16
00:01:44,159 --> 00:01:53,314
But that sense of controlling the body is again coming from a center within us which presumes it has this control.

17
00:01:53,375 --> 00:01:57,200
And that's one of the definitions of self.

18
00:01:57,341 --> 00:02:01,668
One of the definitions of self is that I am in control.

19
00:02:01,867 --> 00:02:15,627
And what happened to the Buddha in his fasting, mainly fasting, was that he just got terribly thin and almost seemingly took himself to a point of death.

20
00:02:15,647 --> 00:02:17,872
He talked about holding his spine through his stomach.

21
00:02:19,193 --> 00:02:20,575
So that's pretty thin.

22
00:02:21,417 --> 00:02:29,769
And at some point he came to recognize that these exercises weren't actually getting him anywhere in the sense that he was still suffering.

23
00:02:30,050 --> 00:02:31,572
That's the point.

24
00:02:32,901 --> 00:02:48,024
Having done those exercises, he came to the conclusion that they were useless, they weren't on the path to liberation, and they were actually suffering, they were actually causing suffering, even though, while you're doing them, there may be a release, a temporary release from hunger.

25
00:02:49,586 --> 00:02:56,817
Those of you who fasted know that after two or three days, there's no appetite really, the body's just feeding itself, frankly.

26
00:02:58,635 --> 00:03:13,043
So that was his own personal rejection of a philosophy or an idea which was current at the time that it was through mortification of the body that one became liberated.

27
00:03:13,302 --> 00:03:18,933
It was the body that was holding the spirit down, this atta, this self, you see.

28
00:03:19,153 --> 00:03:21,859
And once that was done away with, then it would be liberated.

29
00:03:24,015 --> 00:03:34,229
The next thing, of course, the next big awakening moment was seeing these three, what came to be called, messengers from the gods, which is basically sickness, old age and death.

30
00:03:34,709 --> 00:03:46,924
And as the myth goes, I'm sure you know it, he's out on his little hunting party and he comes across somebody who's sick, then there's somebody who's very old and rockety, rickety, and then somebody who's a corpse.

31
00:03:46,943 --> 00:03:48,787
And each time he says, what is it?

32
00:03:49,486 --> 00:03:50,508
And will it happen to me?

33
00:03:50,549 --> 00:03:51,610
Is it?

34
00:03:52,383 --> 00:04:08,604
And it was that connection with what he saw as being something horrific and himself that drew, shall we say, a certain horror about life, about his situation, recognizing that all beings move towards death one way or the other.

35
00:04:09,145 --> 00:04:15,033
If they grow old enough, they just get very sick and lose energy and all that sort of stuff.

36
00:04:15,274 --> 00:04:20,060
So it was that connection with the body that made him seek the end of suffering.

37
00:04:20,362 --> 00:04:24,771
because it manifests, suffering in that sense manifests in the body.

38
00:04:25,853 --> 00:04:32,007
And his first effort was to escape the body completely through what we now call the jhanas, the absorption states.

39
00:04:32,814 --> 00:04:57,269
so in so doing you're creating a mental state and I think he would have understood at that time that the mind or it was understood at that time that the mind could separate from the body so if you began to engender these beautiful states within yourself through mantra practice through breathing just watching the breath calms the body etc.

40
00:04:57,591 --> 00:05:02,096
calms the mind and you go into these beautiful states that therefore

41
00:05:02,076 --> 00:05:09,208
either upon death, or if you were clever enough before it, you would leave the body and enter one of these realms, you see.

42
00:05:10,470 --> 00:05:15,117
And again, to his disappointment, while he was in those states, no problem.

43
00:05:15,137 --> 00:05:23,752
When he came out, he was still sad sack, he was still depressed old Gautama, you see, Siddhartha Gautama.

44
00:05:24,132 --> 00:05:28,860
So he then begins to practice in a completely different way.

45
00:05:30,577 --> 00:05:44,591
through really this memory from childhood, where he's watching his father doing a ploughing ceremony, that memory awakens in him a way of observing the body, a way of actually investigating the process.

46
00:05:45,130 --> 00:05:52,216
Rather than trying to do something with it, rather than trying to change it, he actually discovers a way of just observing it.

47
00:05:52,577 --> 00:05:56,982
So in a sense he's entering into a scientific field, he's entering into a psychology.

48
00:05:57,442 --> 00:06:00,584
He's interested in how does suffering arise, right?

49
00:06:00,564 --> 00:06:12,321
He's left that question as to why, because when you ask why, you start getting into metaphysics, you start wondering why it is, why do all beings suffer, that sort of stuff.

50
00:06:12,341 --> 00:06:22,353
But when he actually draws himself into this mode of observing his mind, observing his body, the question that's coming up is how does it come, how does this happen?

51
00:06:23,060 --> 00:06:31,932
And that's where he eventually becomes liberated and through the liberation begins to describe this dependent origination.

52
00:06:33,194 --> 00:06:37,680
And dependent origination always begins at the point of contact.

53
00:06:38,721 --> 00:06:45,591
And the main point of contact is this contact between the body and the mind.

54
00:06:46,060 --> 00:06:51,355
So it's not as though what the Buddha said that there was a mind-made body.

55
00:06:51,716 --> 00:06:53,180
It's quite clear about that.

56
00:06:53,201 --> 00:06:56,391
There's a physical body and a mind-made body.

57
00:06:57,367 --> 00:07:04,300
And this mind-made body has the same characteristics as the physical body in the sense that it's not permanent.

58
00:07:04,321 --> 00:07:10,072
It itself is a collection or an aggregate of energies.

59
00:07:10,673 --> 00:07:15,502
It's not substantial, but it's still something separate from the physical world.

60
00:07:16,004 --> 00:07:18,649
And that, of course, goes against our principles.

61
00:07:18,629 --> 00:07:27,463
received wisdom from a lot of materialist scientists these days, who reduce everything simply to chemicals and what's measurable.

62
00:07:28,064 --> 00:07:31,790
But in the Buddha's understanding, they were two different forms of energy.

63
00:07:32,851 --> 00:07:39,622
And I think we contact this other form when you contact your own qi, because I don't think that's measurable by any scientific standard.

64
00:07:40,083 --> 00:07:42,526
But you can feel it, you can feel the energy.

65
00:07:42,709 --> 00:07:56,197
And that energy can then move into these mental powers, such as healing.

66
00:07:56,358 --> 00:07:58,322
Healing is actually a mental power.

67
00:07:58,382 --> 00:08:00,245
It doesn't belong to the physical body.

68
00:08:02,369 --> 00:08:12,502
So that separation of the body and mind is one of the first insights that you have on the trail of liberation.

69
00:08:13,223 --> 00:08:22,437
In the process of what we call the vipassana insight process, the first thing is to recognize that the body and mind are actually two different systems.

70
00:08:23,632 --> 00:08:36,711
And when you look into the body, I think one of the first things that sort of surprises you is how little you actually experience of it, unless it goes wrong and you might feel a pain or something.

71
00:08:36,731 --> 00:08:41,258
But there's lots of the body that we're completely unaware of and haven't a clue how it works.

72
00:08:42,179 --> 00:08:44,322
Just a simple thing like toenails.

73
00:08:46,306 --> 00:08:52,254
I mean, you're not a toenail, as you would say, be an emotion, are you?

74
00:08:53,028 --> 00:08:55,211
You can see it, you can feel it, but it's only on the outside.

75
00:08:55,490 --> 00:08:57,312
You can't sort of get into the toenail.

76
00:08:57,894 --> 00:09:01,619
You can't be, in that sense, a toenail.

77
00:09:01,639 --> 00:09:07,125
And yet there it is, growing, just like our hair, or like mine was.

78
00:09:07,144 --> 00:09:11,971
And it's just growing, and we haven't a clue what the process is.

79
00:09:12,051 --> 00:09:16,356
We just presume that it knows what it's doing.

80
00:09:16,376 --> 00:09:18,259
And we also know that...

81
00:09:18,830 --> 00:09:25,442
Things like the marrow of the bone is constantly creating red corpuscles.

82
00:09:27,405 --> 00:09:35,320
When we breathe, we're told that there's this exchange of carbon dioxide with oxygen, but did you ever experience that?

83
00:09:36,480 --> 00:09:37,943
See what I mean?

84
00:09:37,964 --> 00:09:53,679
There's a whole, there's a lot of things that the body's doing which we're completely unaware of, and it's being seemingly guided, it's being run by systems that we are completely unaware of, these autonomic systems.

85
00:09:55,650 --> 00:09:59,620
One of the most amazing things that I came across is the way the eye works.

86
00:10:00,383 --> 00:10:04,934
Because when you look at a picture, the eye seems to be darting here and everywhere.

87
00:10:05,336 --> 00:10:08,363
If you look at the picture of the eye actually moving.

88
00:10:08,484 --> 00:10:13,034
And it's picking up little pixels and sort of taking them into the brain.

89
00:10:13,014 --> 00:10:14,996
But what we keep seeing is the whole picture.

90
00:10:15,037 --> 00:10:17,240
We don't see the eye moving at all.

91
00:10:17,760 --> 00:10:19,221
It's the most strange thing.

92
00:10:20,043 --> 00:10:29,875
And then the brain is able to create a picture which it then somehow launches back onto the retina so that it gives us the impression that we're actually seeing.

93
00:10:30,556 --> 00:10:33,619
We're actually seeing the whole picture or we're looking at the whole person.

94
00:10:35,260 --> 00:10:42,549
And we haven't a clue that all this stuff's going on, but it's not for, you know, clever little cameras hidden in pictures watching people's eyes.

95
00:10:44,065 --> 00:10:48,932
There's one at the National Gallery that shows you how that happens.

96
00:10:48,952 --> 00:10:59,530
So it's that as you begin to investigate the body, even at this intellectual level, you begin to realize that you're an alien within this frame.

97
00:11:00,371 --> 00:11:02,174
Like there's this sense of me.

98
00:11:02,527 --> 00:11:08,956
You've got this me, me in there, but it's not in control at all.

99
00:11:09,657 --> 00:11:20,293
And that's how, that's why we're terribly upset and baffled as to why illnesses arise within the body over which we not only don't have a control, but didn't even know it was there, you know.

100
00:11:22,235 --> 00:11:25,480
Autonomic diseases, you know.

101
00:11:26,640 --> 00:11:33,131
Things like multiple cirrhosis and stuff where the body seems to just do its own thing.

102
00:11:33,953 --> 00:11:39,703
I had a student down in Gaia House and his body started eating his own liver.

103
00:11:40,325 --> 00:11:41,105
Can you figure that out?

104
00:11:42,216 --> 00:11:43,238
for no apparent reason.

105
00:11:43,739 --> 00:11:56,096
I mean, they've got drugs to sort of delay the process, but it's that whole business of suddenly recognizing that where as a child we think we are the body, we are the body.

106
00:11:56,236 --> 00:11:58,620
There's no distinction really in our mind.

107
00:11:59,181 --> 00:12:07,633
Slowly, he's going to realize actually there is this sense of self, there is this sense of a me, a presence within this body, which

108
00:12:07,917 --> 00:12:11,663
It can superficially move the body about.

109
00:12:11,884 --> 00:12:14,067
You can wave your arms in the air and stuff like that.

110
00:12:14,467 --> 00:12:26,347
When it comes to the real things that you do want to have control over, which is the health of the body and the longevity of the body, and we don't particularly want to die, no control whatsoever.

111
00:12:26,682 --> 00:12:55,794
and that coming in contact with that may raise within us you know these fears these anxieties and what not and what that is measuring is this delusion that the Buddha talks about as to where is this me where is it so in the Buddha's teaching the investigation of the body the contemplation of the body is absolutely crucial in undermining this essential delusion about who we are see

112
00:12:57,039 --> 00:13:04,549
I mean the other delusions are to think that we are an emotion, to think that we are feelings, to think that we are thoughts.

113
00:13:06,052 --> 00:13:17,648
If you look at it from more of a Western point of view, there's the body, there's the heart with its feelings and emotional life and all that, and there's the mind with its thought life.

114
00:13:17,628 --> 00:13:32,288
And through meditation, through your vipassana, you're taking an objective stance outside these three areas and recognizing that there's a distance between that which is observing and what's being observed.

115
00:13:33,889 --> 00:13:41,059
And it's that distance which is, as it were, informing this, that which is looking, that it's not that.

116
00:13:41,220 --> 00:13:41,981
It can't be that.

117
00:13:42,081 --> 00:13:43,964
You can't be an object.

118
00:13:44,804 --> 00:13:46,347
You can only be the subject.

119
00:13:47,349 --> 00:13:47,448
Yeah?

120
00:13:50,837 --> 00:14:09,758
so these exercises that we were doing the one about the repulsive nature of the body is right there within the discourse on how to establish right awareness in other words right understanding leading to right understanding and that particular exercise is a

121
00:14:09,738 --> 00:14:25,840
an interesting occasion in the scriptures, which is rather strange really, in terms of the Buddha's general teaching, where some monks have been practicing this repulsiveness of the body all through the rainy season, that's three months thinking about how repulsive the body is.

122
00:14:25,820 --> 00:14:38,235
And he sees them coming towards him and maybe has a discussion with them or whatever, but he recognizes that they've gone over from seeing the body as repulsive to actually being repulsed by the body.

123
00:14:38,856 --> 00:14:40,621
There's two different things, right?

124
00:14:41,394 --> 00:14:46,947
The reason we're doing that exercise is to go beyond disgust of the body.

125
00:14:47,788 --> 00:14:48,890
But we're not...

126
00:14:48,910 --> 00:14:57,250
If you go too far about the repulsion of the body, to your dismay, you may find you're getting more disgusted with the body.

127
00:14:57,549 --> 00:14:58,812
So it's a case of...

128
00:14:59,570 --> 00:15:14,072
investigating the body to catch that sense of disgust that we have about it, or the sense of ugliness we have about it, and then to allow that to pass away, you see, so that we then become equanimous with the body.

129
00:15:14,332 --> 00:15:18,239
The body is just as it is, and we're perfectly content with the way it is.

130
00:15:18,480 --> 00:15:20,042
That's where we want to get to.

131
00:15:20,022 --> 00:15:22,988
So he saw that maybe they'd gone over the edge.

132
00:15:23,207 --> 00:15:26,394
So he gave them the practice of loving kindness towards the body.

133
00:15:27,576 --> 00:15:30,703
And all these tales end off marvelously.

134
00:15:30,724 --> 00:15:33,929
They all became fully liberated through this practice.

135
00:15:35,243 --> 00:15:44,937
The commentaries always gloss that with after 25 years in the forest or something like that.

136
00:15:45,357 --> 00:16:03,124
So the exercise that we were doing at the beginning concerning the business about finding areas of the body that we have this disgust towards, that may be a too stronger word sometimes, but it's the only word that sort of gets across that visceral feel about certain things of the body.

137
00:16:04,690 --> 00:16:07,393
and the bit about our self-image.

138
00:16:08,793 --> 00:16:33,499
We're using it to actually get in contact with the fullness of that self-image that we have of ourselves and then to allow the feelings around that self-image to really come up clearly in the mind and to observe them and observe them long enough to see that in fact they die away because you're no longer feeding in to that delusion.

139
00:16:33,765 --> 00:16:57,798
and that's important if if these feelings of disgust or fear and all that sort of stuff around the body come up and we don't wait long enough we don't see that the process of just observing just feeling just allowing these things to express themselves is actually the therapy if you if you if you stay until they come up strongly then you say I've had enough of this and walk off

140
00:16:58,318 --> 00:17:03,446
And you may be under the impression that actually all you're doing is just lifting up the disgust and feeling disgusted all the time.

141
00:17:04,067 --> 00:17:10,737
So these exercises have to be taken, you have to sort of practice them until you see that in fact it's fading.

142
00:17:11,718 --> 00:17:19,950
If you've got the patience to stay until it completely faded, that's even better because then that really is undermining the conditioning.

143
00:17:19,970 --> 00:17:22,413
But if you haven't, at least to see the way it goes.

144
00:17:23,173 --> 00:17:27,059
That's not only within the body, but of course within our emotional life.

145
00:17:27,039 --> 00:17:32,788
When we feel depressed or we feel anxious, if we can just go into the body, see, forget the mind.

146
00:17:32,848 --> 00:17:37,395
Remember, emotional states are always developing themselves through the mind.

147
00:17:37,415 --> 00:17:39,479
That's how they develop themselves through stories.

148
00:17:40,740 --> 00:17:45,488
That's why when you go into Vipassana, the teacher is not at all interested in your stories.

149
00:17:45,468 --> 00:17:52,480
Either historical, whether they're true or not, they're not actually part of the process of healing.

150
00:17:52,500 --> 00:17:59,932
It's letting them go and getting down to the root feeling that's been there, the rooted mental state, emotional state.

151
00:18:00,519 --> 00:18:11,855
Allowing that to arise and to let it express itself, to expend itself, and in so doing you see this fading away.

152
00:18:13,077 --> 00:18:17,324
So that's how it also works in terms of just our emotional life in general.

153
00:18:18,285 --> 00:18:23,372
Just to be able to hold on in there and wait for it to slowly fade away.

154
00:18:25,359 --> 00:18:33,875
So that's part of the teaching around dukkha, which means suffering, hard to bear, hard to bear.

155
00:18:34,675 --> 00:18:37,401
And there are three types of suffering.

156
00:18:37,421 --> 00:18:41,407
So the first one we've been discussing is what's called the dukkha dukkha.

157
00:18:41,428 --> 00:18:43,571
It's the suffering of ordinary pain.

158
00:18:44,057 --> 00:18:55,540
And with that, there comes the pain that is caused by identity, which we contact through sickness, old age and death.

159
00:18:55,560 --> 00:18:57,444
And that's a very strong meditation.

160
00:18:58,207 --> 00:19:03,837
I mentioned this business of the charnel grounds and the cemetery meditations.

161
00:19:03,817 --> 00:19:28,864
And, you know, it's just one of those paradoxes that if you spend a moment every day just contemplating one's own, the possibility of sickness or rage and death, and then to, you always have to balance it with loving kindness towards yourself, it actually has the ultimate effect of taking away irrational fears about sickness or rage and death.

162
00:19:29,417 --> 00:19:33,762
One of the things about sickness is that the mind produces a future.

163
00:19:34,523 --> 00:19:37,727
So as soon as you're sick it's always going to be like this.

164
00:19:37,747 --> 00:19:44,674
As soon as you've got something wrong with the body, the mind immediately creates this huge plan where you're going to keep suffering forever.

165
00:19:46,396 --> 00:19:53,163
But actually when you come down to the experience of the sickness, just as it is in this present moment,

166
00:19:53,683 --> 00:20:02,333
All you have, and I'm talking about just ordinary illness, I mean obviously there are some which are extraordinarily painful, all you have is discomfort and some disability.

167
00:20:03,032 --> 00:20:06,196
You know, you have to get out, you can't do what you normally do.

168
00:20:07,218 --> 00:20:21,632
And when you come into an ordinary illness, I'm talking about flus and colds and things that aren't so bad, when you come into that sort of present experience of the illness, it's okay.

169
00:20:22,777 --> 00:20:25,400
But the mind wants to go beyond it.

170
00:20:25,480 --> 00:20:27,561
The mind, first of all, is very negative.

171
00:20:27,623 --> 00:20:29,384
It wants to create this terrible future.

172
00:20:29,424 --> 00:20:30,144
It's going to get worse.

173
00:20:31,126 --> 00:20:33,128
And secondly, it wants to escape.

174
00:20:33,789 --> 00:20:37,854
So we're constantly in contradiction with what's actually happening.

175
00:20:38,454 --> 00:20:48,125
But when all that goes, and we just clear the mind of all that, we just sink into the present moment, and that's why there's this constant reminder to be present in the present moment.

176
00:20:48,105 --> 00:20:53,432
What you find with most illnesses is this discomfort and a disability.

177
00:20:54,775 --> 00:20:55,476
And it's bearable.

178
00:20:55,737 --> 00:20:56,176
That's the point.

179
00:20:56,196 --> 00:20:56,798
It's bearable.

180
00:20:57,558 --> 00:21:02,605
There are very few illnesses that, you know, one would consider to be completely unbearable.

181
00:21:04,970 --> 00:21:13,642
And I mentioned this morning, when pain gets to a point where, you know, we're not learning anything from it, etc., then, you know, it's good to put an end to it.

182
00:21:14,282 --> 00:21:15,243
Try to put an end to it.

183
00:21:16,422 --> 00:21:23,810
And I'm not suggesting there that in extreme cases one should commit suicide.

184
00:21:23,830 --> 00:21:26,933
That's always a moot point in Buddhism.

185
00:21:26,993 --> 00:21:31,500
Generally speaking, it's quite clear the Buddha didn't support suicide.

186
00:21:32,760 --> 00:21:40,269
But there are two instances which, shall we say, are interesting.

187
00:21:40,704 --> 00:21:48,523
One is of a monk who is despairing about his practice, and in his despair, he kills himself.

188
00:21:48,544 --> 00:21:54,478
And when the Buddha comes along, he says that, no, he's in that moment of dying, he actually became liberated.

189
00:21:55,505 --> 00:22:10,736
So one presumes that even in that desperate moment, just to be able to take the position of the observer and to actually see what's happening in a very clear way would liberate you from that, from delusion.

190
00:22:11,457 --> 00:22:12,720
But I wouldn't chance it.

191
00:22:13,290 --> 00:22:16,376
I wouldn't risk it, personally.

192
00:22:17,419 --> 00:22:27,478
And the other one is, an interesting one, is of an Arahant, he's fully liberated, who is suffering, obviously, from some very severe, very painful state.

193
00:22:27,999 --> 00:22:32,768
And in those days, of course, they wouldn't have had anaesthetics in the sense that we have.

194
00:22:32,748 --> 00:22:39,242
So in that terrible pain, he says to the Buddha, he's going to take the knife, that's how he would express it, and he kills himself.

195
00:22:39,564 --> 00:22:43,011
And the Buddha didn't say, the Buddha doesn't make decisions for you.

196
00:22:43,051 --> 00:22:51,111
If you watch the Buddha, he doesn't, if you come to the Buddha with a question, he doesn't say, don't do this or that, he just says, do what you think is fit.

197
00:22:51,090 --> 00:22:54,234
So, in other words, you're the one who has the responsibility.

198
00:22:54,255 --> 00:22:57,660
You don't go to the Buddha and say, what would you tell me to do?

199
00:22:57,880 --> 00:22:59,182
He's not prepared to do that.

200
00:22:59,762 --> 00:23:02,205
He always says, well, you do what you think is fit.

201
00:23:02,446 --> 00:23:06,092
So, he commits suicide.

202
00:23:06,772 --> 00:23:13,902
But you have to be careful of that because this particular person was fully liberated.

203
00:23:14,063 --> 00:23:18,769
So, in a sense, one has to put a question mark over that.

204
00:23:21,736 --> 00:23:27,442
So that's looking at it from the point of view of suffering, the suffering which is caused by pain.

205
00:23:27,983 --> 00:23:33,891
And the distinction we have to make is that pain is pain coming from the body and it's not suffering.

206
00:23:34,371 --> 00:23:45,684
Once we can get that angle on it of observing it, allowing it to be, relaxing around it, being open to it, then it's not actually causing suffering.

207
00:23:47,317 --> 00:23:51,844
And the second thing is this dispense of impermanence.

208
00:23:51,864 --> 00:23:56,951
One of the things that the self defines itself by is that it's permanent.

209
00:23:56,971 --> 00:23:57,791
It never changes.

210
00:23:58,932 --> 00:23:59,673
It's always happy.

211
00:23:59,874 --> 00:24:04,619
I mean that's how you define a spirit or self or a soul or something.

212
00:24:05,501 --> 00:24:13,511
And the whole process of observing impermanence is one of the routes whereby you can liberate yourself.

213
00:24:14,285 --> 00:24:22,182
So just to bring it up, you know, as a daily little meditation that, you know, things change, everything changes.

214
00:24:22,201 --> 00:24:28,115
It stops you clinging on to things, stops us from expecting things to be as they ought to be.

215
00:24:28,516 --> 00:24:32,344
It's us which put these oughts and musts on situations.

216
00:24:32,324 --> 00:24:37,714
But it's just relaxing around that and accepting that everything is impermanent, everything is in a process of change.

217
00:24:38,435 --> 00:24:51,362
And that this change is impossible to know in any absolute sense which way something is going to change because there are so many factors that come into any given situation.

218
00:24:51,696 --> 00:24:52,798
So you simply don't know.

219
00:24:54,200 --> 00:24:58,124
And resting in that situation of don't know is very difficult for us.

220
00:24:58,804 --> 00:25:03,189
Because one of the things that the self wants to do is to be in charge, to be in control.

221
00:25:03,469 --> 00:25:05,111
And if you want to be in control, you've got to know.

222
00:25:06,352 --> 00:25:17,063
So all these little things that come up for us are quite little awakeners which point to this essential delusion that lies within us.

223
00:25:18,898 --> 00:25:29,549
Now the gift of investigating dukkha, investigating this sense of suffering that we have about things, is of course happiness.

224
00:25:30,750 --> 00:25:34,515
Because you move towards being at ease with the world as it is.

225
00:25:35,596 --> 00:25:41,762
One of the gifts of impermanence is that you begin to let go much more easily.

226
00:25:42,202 --> 00:25:47,808
And you begin to realize in the Buddhist world that there's nothing in the world worth holding on to.

227
00:25:49,190 --> 00:26:19,112
and if you keep repeating that to yourself let it sink in there's nothing in the world worth holding on to worth holding on to nothing in the world it's all that sinks in that there is actually nothing in the world worth holding on to and that makes us very easy with things and it expresses itself through an easy generosity an easy forgiveness you don't hold on to things

228
00:26:21,049 --> 00:26:25,876
And then finally there's this self, this idea of who we are.

229
00:26:26,298 --> 00:26:31,885
So the investigation of the body is constantly undermining that basic identity.

230
00:26:32,647 --> 00:26:34,951
And it's understandable it comes to us at birth.

231
00:26:36,113 --> 00:26:44,204
Very shortly after birth, at some time in early childhood, there's a growing idea of me as opposed to something else.

232
00:26:44,184 --> 00:26:52,739
I mean, they tell us, psychologists tell us that up to about the age of four, we don't seem to have an object.

233
00:26:53,078 --> 00:26:55,804
It's just one mass of swimming sensations.

234
00:26:56,505 --> 00:26:57,125
And it's all us.

235
00:26:57,586 --> 00:27:00,351
There's no distinction between me and somebody else.

236
00:27:01,011 --> 00:27:03,736
And out of that looms the first object, it seems, your mother.

237
00:27:04,557 --> 00:27:09,265
And then we move to this point where everything around us is objective to us.

238
00:27:09,380 --> 00:27:15,172
So by the age of, I don't know, somewhere between two and three, I suppose, one is quite clear that I'm me and everybody else is not me.

239
00:27:16,034 --> 00:27:18,278
I might not phrase it like that, but it's quite clear.

240
00:27:19,079 --> 00:27:22,826
But that child is entirely the body.

241
00:27:23,048 --> 00:27:31,084
There's no distinction between somebody in the body, observing the body, they are just the body.

242
00:27:31,064 --> 00:27:41,818
And I often say, well, if you want to know what it's like to be a body self, just catch the next time you trap your finger in the door.

243
00:27:41,838 --> 00:27:45,924
Because just for that one glorious moment, you are the pain.

244
00:27:46,965 --> 00:27:49,990
There's just that complete flooding of your consciousness pain.

245
00:27:50,050 --> 00:27:50,951
You are the pain.

246
00:27:51,873 --> 00:27:52,794
That's the body self.

247
00:27:54,236 --> 00:28:00,345
And that's why physical pain to children is all the more acute than it is to an adult.

248
00:28:02,029 --> 00:28:10,881
Now all we're doing in this process of liberation is turning the inside world into an outside world.

249
00:28:10,901 --> 00:28:23,277
So just as the child has turned this complete me into something objective, the world that it can feel, see and talk to, so as we move inward, that's all we're doing.

250
00:28:24,097 --> 00:28:29,184
So this body is the walls of this room.

251
00:28:29,451 --> 00:28:33,117
So you're looking at the walls of your own inner self, you might say.

252
00:28:34,079 --> 00:28:38,126
And the atmosphere of the room is your emotional life.

253
00:28:38,146 --> 00:28:41,011
And all the pictures and writings and all that are your thoughts.

254
00:28:41,893 --> 00:28:45,839
And when they all come together you get this human being.

255
00:28:46,326 --> 00:29:07,575
but by observing all that you are finding a very different place within yourself and that is the observer, the feeler, the knower, the experiencer that level of consciousness has the ability to both understand and to feel and yet to be quite objective towards his experiencing

256
00:29:07,555 --> 00:29:17,498
And that objectivity, seeing the inner world as objective, is the process of undermining the delusion that we are

257
00:29:17,983 --> 00:29:22,853
the body, we are sensations, we are emotions, we are thoughts.

258
00:29:24,315 --> 00:29:41,967
So the exercises that we were doing was really also to do, especially the one about sickness, old age and death, observing that, getting in touch with that, is that process of deconstructing the whole of the world that we are creating

259
00:29:42,672 --> 00:29:49,424
and beginning to realize that there is something within that which has this power to understand

260
00:29:50,704 --> 00:29:59,758
And this knowing is what actually liberates itself, because the delusion lies in the looking.

261
00:30:00,278 --> 00:30:05,806
The delusion lies within the way we relate, and that is in our understanding.

262
00:30:06,326 --> 00:30:12,655
And the understanding is this knowing, this part of us which is our pure intelligence.

263
00:30:12,675 --> 00:30:19,345
That's why I call this place Satipaññā, because sati is the passive,

264
00:30:19,695 --> 00:30:46,512
form of the enlightenment which is that which receives and that's why the exercise we do in standing is so important because it's actually developing that open-minded, open-hearted reception without any barrier and the paññā is that very same faculty which sparks and understands the way things are so one is passive and one is active

265
00:30:46,492 --> 00:30:50,079
The paññā is described as an intuitive faculty.

266
00:30:50,701 --> 00:30:56,873
So often you get this translated variously as intuitive awareness or awareness with intuitive intelligence or whatever.

267
00:30:57,473 --> 00:30:59,438
But that's the Buddha within.

268
00:30:59,538 --> 00:31:00,420
That's what we are.

269
00:31:00,861 --> 00:31:02,864
That's what's becoming awake.

270
00:31:03,305 --> 00:31:06,290
That's what's awakening to its circumstance.

271
00:31:08,396 --> 00:31:23,992
So in doing these exercises, the ones to do with sickness, old age and death, and the disgust and the ugliness, and then also, I forgot to mention, the business where you recognize that

272
00:31:24,461 --> 00:31:30,248
a lot of our happiness is dependent upon the actual sense body.

273
00:31:31,470 --> 00:31:35,013
And once you realize that, you realize that there's potentially a lot of suffering.

274
00:31:35,574 --> 00:31:42,662
So this exercise is trying to undermine that by, as it were, recognizing that we don't have control.

275
00:31:43,722 --> 00:31:46,486
And in not having control, we have to accept the way things are.

276
00:31:46,686 --> 00:31:50,570
And in that acceptance, there is the peacefulness.

277
00:31:51,714 --> 00:31:55,840
So always make a distinction between acceptance and resignation.

278
00:31:55,901 --> 00:32:01,589
Resignation is saying, well, this is the reason I can't do anything about it, and it's all horrible, and I may as well go and jump off a bridge.

279
00:32:02,151 --> 00:32:03,172
I mean, that's resignation.

280
00:32:03,192 --> 00:32:05,516
But acceptance is, this is the way it is.

281
00:32:05,977 --> 00:32:06,857
This is the way it is.

282
00:32:07,439 --> 00:32:14,769
And in seeing the way it is, always something arises, some potential arises, because everything's moving, everything's changing.

283
00:32:19,171 --> 00:32:41,009
And so finally, having undermined these different misunderstandings about how we create, about what happiness is, etc., about impermanence and permanence, about self and not-self, we then have to, as it were, begin to take that understanding into an attitude.

284
00:32:41,294 --> 00:32:48,304
And that attitude is one of reconnecting with the body and that's why the love is so important.

285
00:32:48,664 --> 00:33:00,281
Because now having distance from the body and having seen that it's capable of creating a lot of suffering for us, we then have to go back into that body and embrace it in all its fullness.

286
00:33:01,190 --> 00:33:02,330
That's the same with the mind.

287
00:33:02,771 --> 00:33:16,587
When you open yourself up to these negative emotions within us, and we're allowing them to express themselves, we then have to return to our emotional life, our heart, with loving-kindness to embrace it.

288
00:33:17,189 --> 00:33:19,372
And the same with thoughts.

289
00:33:19,392 --> 00:33:29,002
So in so doing, we are developing a different relationship to the experiences that we're having in the world.

290
00:33:30,096 --> 00:33:57,403
and it's based upon this acceptance of the way things really are the openness to allow the things that really are to express themselves and then to pour back into the situation a really good energy and that's the purpose of the exercises we're doing specifically to the body but when we're doing vipassana and then we end with metta we're doing it for the heart and the mind

291
00:33:58,025 --> 00:34:05,034
And very slowly, you see, there's this development, development of the spiritual life.

292
00:34:05,054 --> 00:34:07,076
That's what we mean by the spiritual life.

293
00:34:07,096 --> 00:34:14,365
As opposed to a simple, you know, psychotherapeutic life or a physical, a life based on just your physicality.

294
00:34:15,467 --> 00:34:23,998
The word spiritual is a bit, you know, it's got all sorts of tags attached to it, but it's about the only word I think we have which makes sense.

295
00:34:23,978 --> 00:34:36,416
I mean, the other one you might use is, you know, the growth of consciousness, but these days that's becoming really sort of somehow confused with the contents of consciousness.

296
00:34:36,637 --> 00:34:38,740
So it's all these words, you know.

297
00:34:38,760 --> 00:34:41,023
But it becomes clear to us through our practice.

298
00:34:41,605 --> 00:34:48,635
It becomes clear to us through our practice that there is something within us which can be entirely objective,

299
00:34:49,139 --> 00:34:55,887
to the body, heart and mind, to the whole psycho-physical process, and yet be completely at one with it.

300
00:34:57,389 --> 00:35:04,197
And that's why, when you're in meditation, you're making this effort to objectify everything and to understand everything.

301
00:35:04,958 --> 00:35:07,282
When you're doing metta, you're redirecting.

302
00:35:07,742 --> 00:35:16,193
But when you get up, you see, this is the point, when you get up, and that's why I stress it in the work period, your attention and care go into what you're doing.

303
00:35:16,730 --> 00:35:21,737
And there's a loss, at best, there's a loss of a sense of somebody doing something.

304
00:35:24,280 --> 00:35:26,744
And that's enlightenment in action.

305
00:35:26,784 --> 00:35:30,530
That's the process of awareness in action.

306
00:35:40,264 --> 00:35:42,788
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

307
00:35:44,438 --> 00:35:59,510
May you be liberated from all suffering and delusion and enter into that blissful state of nibbana, the deathless, sooner rather than later.

